{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"51e3ff3b-f192-4ea8-a579-f8d1a35ac142","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio server\n\nRun the Inspector via `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:6274`) that acts as an MCP client. It spawns your server as a child process using stdio.\n\n**In the Inspector UI you can:**\n- Browse **Tools**, **Resources**, and **Prompts** your server exposes\n- Invoke tools with custom JSON inputs and see responses\n- View the raw JSON-RPC messages for debugging\n\n**Tips:**\n- If your server needs args, append them: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./Server.csproj -- --my-flag`\n- Use `--server-url` if you need a custom port.\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** and logs to **stderr** — any stray stdout output will break the protocol.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"59ba6a9b-35ec-469c-a0dd-5fc11176d0d1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling - I don't need to search a codebase for this. Let me provide a concise, helpful answer.","outputTokens":319,"requestId":"5029:348511:AF847A:CACAF9:69F2AAEE"},"id":"74919517-5d6f-49f0-9664-374aae3b33a5","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:07:13.631Z","parentId":"93da0b22-9cf3-4b14-ad4f-22b8b6885bf3"}
